 person and highlights the role of women in slave societies.Serving as the third book in the UTP/CHA International Themes and Issues Series, Shaping the New World introduces readers to the topic of African slavery in the New World from a comparative perspective, specifically focusing on the English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, and Dutch slave systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAntislavery movementszAmericaxHistory. 0aSlave tradezAfricaxHistory. 0aSlavery - Brazil - History. 0aSlaveryzAmericaxHistory. 0aSlaveryzBrazilxHistory. 0aSlaveryzCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aSlaveryzLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aSlaveryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSlavery--America--History. 0aSlaveszAmericaxSocial conditions. 4aCoursebook. 7aHISTORY / Americas (North, Central, South, West Indies).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144260556540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442605565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442605565/original  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK